-- JSW Steel, Bharat Heavy, Essar Oil, Tech Mahindra: India Equity Preview
-- Rajhkumar K Shaaw
-- 2010-07-27T03:00:07Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-27/bharat-heavy-electricals-essar-oil-tech-mahindra-india-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following companies may have
 unusual  price changes in India  trading . Stock symbols are in
parentheses and share prices are as of the  last close .  
 The Bombay Stock Exchange’s Sensitive Index, or  Sensex ,
declined 110.93, or 0.6 percent, to 18,020.05. The S&P CNX  Nifty 
Index on the National Stock Exchange lost 0.6 percent to
5,418.60. The  BSE 200 Index  retreated 0.6 percent to 2,291.32.
The  SGX S&P CNX Nifty Index futures  for July delivery increased
0.4 to 5,440 at 10:42 a.m. in Singapore.  
 Metals stocks:  Sesa Goa Ltd.  (SESA IN) and  Sterlite
Industries (India) Ltd.  (STLT IN) were added to UBS AG’s model
portfolio on the view that concerns the global economic recovery
will falter has weighed on metals-related shares and made their
valuations more “attractive.”  
 Maruti Suzuki India Ltd.  (MSIL IN) was removed from the
portfolio after being downgraded to “neutral” from “buy,”
because of narrower margins, UBS analyst  Suresh A Mahadevan 
wrote in a report.  
 Sesa, India’s biggest iron-ore exporter, climbed 0.3
percent to 366.1 rupees. Sterlite, the largest copper and zinc
producer, fell 0.1 percent to 173.85 rupees. Maruti plunged 12
percent to 1,191.45 rupees.  
 Bharat Heavy Electricals Ltd.  (BHEL IN): India’s biggest
power equipment maker was downgraded to “add” from “buy” by
 Devang Patel , an analyst at Avendus Capital Pvt., with a share-
price estimate of 2,787 rupees. Bharat Heavy rose 0.5 percent to
2,471.35 rupees.  
 Dabur India Ltd.  (DABUR IN): The maker of products ranging
from shampoos to beverages was cut to “reduce” from “buy” by
Nomura Holdings Inc. analysts  Manish Jain  and  Anup Sudhendranath ,
who cited the “strong run-up” in the stock since the start of
the year. The analysts have a share-price estimate of 193 rupees
for Dabur. The stock fell 3.8 percent to 203.55 rupees.  
  Essar Oil Ltd.  (ESOIL IN): India’s second-biggest non-state
refiner had a first-quarter loss of 700 million rupees ($14.9
million) compared with a profit of 1.7 billion rupees a year
earlier, the company said in an e-mailed statement. Sales rose
52 percent, the statement said. The stock declined 1.9 percent
to 130.5 rupees.  
 Hero Honda Motors Ltd.  (HH IN):  Honda Motor Co.,  Japan’s
second-biggest carmaker, denied it is selling a stake in  Hero
Honda Motors Ltd. , maker of half the motorcycles in India.  
 CNBC-TV18 reported on July 23 that Honda might sell about 6
percent of the New Delhi-based motorcycle maker, without saying
where it got the information. Hero Honda sank 7.5 percent to
1,804.3 rupees.  
 JSW Steel Ltd.  (JSTL IN):  JFE Holdings Inc ., Japan’s
second-largest steelmaker, may announce plans to invest about $1
billion in the Indian steel producer as soon as today, said two
people with direct knowledge of the deal. JFE will meet
reporters at 1 p.m. in Tokyo to announce a business alliance
with JSW, according to a notice posted at an industry press
association in Japan. JSW declined 2.2 percent to 1,171 rupees.  
 National Aluminium Co.  (NACL IN): India’s government may
allow the metal producer to issue free shares and split the
stock to boost liquidity, the Financial Chronicle reported,
citing a mines ministry official it didn’t identify. The state-
owned metals producer prefers a stock split to selling a stake
in the company, the newspaper said. The stock fell 0.1 percent
to 435.1 rupees.  
 NTPC Ltd.  (NATP IN): Profit at Asia’s second largest power
producer by market value unexpectedly declined 16 percent to
18.4 billion rupees last quarter from a year earlier. That’s
lower than the 22.5 billion rupees mean estimate of 27 analysts
surveyed by Bloomberg. The stock fell 0.1 percent to 201.75
rupees.  
 Tech Mahindra Ltd.  (TECHM IN): The software company that
acquired Satyam Computer Services Ltd. had first-quarter profit
of 1.28 billion rupees, according to a statement sent to the
Bombay Stock Exchange.  
 Separately, the company was cut to “neutral” from
“overweight” by JPMorgan Chase & Co. analysts  Nishit Jasani 
and  Viju K George . The shares fell 1.2 percent to 737.55 rupees.  
 Vishal Retail Ltd.  (VISH IN): Lenders to the retailer may
support a debt recast proposal from Future Group, disregarding
an offer from private equity investor TPG Capital, the Economic
Times reported, citing people it didn’t identify. The stock
declined 2.3 percent to 49.1 rupees.  
